member.example:
The following example show how to draw different objects on the page
using different logical units to position them.

...
PDFPen pen = new PDFPen( new PDFColor( 255, 0, 0 ), 1 );
PDFDocument doc = new PDFDocument( );
PDFPage page = doc.AddPage( );
page.LogicalUnit = new PDFMMLogicalUnit( );
// the following drawing operation uses the millimeter
// as a logical unit to draw the line. The milimeter
// was defined as default logical unit for the page.
page.Canvas.DrawLine( pen, 10, 10, 100, 100 );

page.Canvas.SetLogicalUnit( new PDFPointLogicalUnit( ) );
// the following drawing operation uses the point, as requested above,
// to draw the line.
page.Canvas.DrawLine( pen, 20, 10, 110, 100 );
...

The following example sets the direction of the Y axis to be from
bottom to top. It also sets the origin of the coordinate system to
bottom left corner of the page (this is the default coordinate system
used by pdf files). The sample assumes the current origin of the coordinate
system is at top left corner of the page.

...
page.Canvas.SetOrigin( 0, page.Height );
page.Canvas.SetAxesDirection( XAxisDirection.LeftToRight, YAxisDirection.BottomToTop );
// the default pdf coordinate system is now in place
...

The following example shows how to set several custom properties
for a document:

...
PDFDocument doc = new PDFDocument( );

PDFMetadataSchema schema = new PDFMetadataSchema( );
schema.Name = "http://ns.o2sol.com/schema/pdf/1.4/";
schema.NamespacePrefix = "o2s";

// set Company attribute
schema["Company"] = "O2 Solutions";
// set Website attribute
schema["Website"] = "http://www.o2sol.com/";

// Add schema to the document
doc.MetadataSchemas.Add( schema );
...

member.remarks:
This method splits a pdf file to individual pages. Each page is named
            using destFileName parameter after which a numeric index is appended, eg: 
            destfileName001.pdf, destfileName002.pdf, destfileName003.pdf, etc.
